Spanish Stocks: Iberdrola Renovables, Natraceutical, Telefonica

-- B y   M a n u e l   B a i g o r r i
-- 
2011-03-02T16:47:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-02/spanish-stocks-iberdrola-renovables-iberdrola-telefonica-move.html
Spain’s  IBEX 35 index  fell for a
second day, losing 118.1, or 1.1 percent, to 10,643.8 at the
5:30 p.m. close in Madrid. The Madrid Stock Exchange General
Index also dropped 1.1 percent.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
Spanish market. Symbols are in parentheses after company names.    Iberdrola Renovables SA  (IBR SM) sank 1.8 percent to 2.68
euros, breaking four days of gains. The clean-energy unit of
Spain’s  Iberdrola SA  (IBE SM) said it will limit investments in
2012 as it aims to increase profitability. The company said it
plans total new capacity of 1,450 megawatts in 2011 and 750
megawatts in 2012. Iberdrola shares fell 1.6 percent to 6.13
euros.    Natraceutical SA  (NTC SM) sank 4 percent to 36.2 euro
cents, a second straight loss and the biggest decline in almost
five months. The maker of natural extracts for foods and
cosmetics was cut to “sell” from “buy” at Caja Madrid Bolsa.    NH Hoteles SA  (NHH SM) climbed for a second day, adding 2
percent to 4.68 euros. The hotelier was raised to “neutral”
from “reduce” at Natixis.  Sacyr Vallehermoso SA (SYV SM) rose 0.9 percent to 8.05
euros, erasing yesterday’s drop. A group of companies including
Sacyr won a contract valued at 95.1 million euros ($132 million)
to build part of a railway in the Basque region.  Telefonica SA (TEF SM) fell 1.4 percent to 18.14 euros, its
first decline in five days.  Jazztel Plc  (JAZ SM) overtook
Spain’s biggest phone company for the first time in signing new
broadband Internet customers last year, Expansion reported,
citing the Spanish telecommunications regulator and the
companies. Jazztel shares dropped 1.6 percent to 3.84 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Manuel Baigorri in Madrid at 
 mbaigorri@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at 
 dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 